                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.002/431: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-31T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 31, 1937—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>390. Reference Shanghai’s 1240, December 28, 1 p.m. Although the Department feels
                    that you should not make this development the occasion for a special visit to
                    the Japanese Foreign Office, the Department desires that in future conversations
                    held in accordance with paragraph 4 of the Department’s telegram No. 383,
                    December 29, 5 p.m., in regard to the general question of the integrity of the
                    Chinese Maritime Customs, you place some emphasis upon the damaging effect upon
                    the Customs administration of disregard of customs requirements for Japanese
                    goods and vessels, particularly as described in paragraph 2 of Shanghai’s No.
                    1240.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Shanghai and Hankow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
